{"cursor":"32154","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n{{Infobox medical person |name = Oliver Sacks |image =\n9.13.09OliverSacksByLuigiNovi.jpg |caption = Sacks at the 2009 Brooklyn Book\nFestival |birth_name=Oliver Wolf Sacks |birth_date = |birth_place = London,\nEngland |death_date = |death_place = |profession = Physician |specialty =\nNeurology |known_for = Popular books containing case studies of some of his\npatients |years_active= }} 'Oliver Wolf Sacks', CBE (born 9 July 1933), is a British-\nAmerican neurologist, writer, and amateur chemist who is Professor of Neurology\nat New York University School of Medicine. Between 2007 and 2012, he was\nprofessor of neurology and psychiatry at Columbia University, where he also held\nthe position of \"Columbia Artist\". Before that, he spent many years on the\nclinical faculty of Yeshiva University's Albert Einstein College of Medicine. He\nalso holds the position of visiting professor at the United Kingdom's University\nof Warwick. [http://www.newswise.com/articles/nyu-langone-medical-center-welcomes-\nneurologist-and-author-oliver-sacks-md \"NYU Langone Medical Center Welcomes\nNeurologist and Author Oliver Sacks, MD\"]. newswise.com. September 13,\n2012.\n\nSacks is the author of numerous best-selling books, Authors Oliver\nSacks|work=About the Author|publisher=Random House|accessdate=5 March\n2009}} including several collections of case studies of people with\nneurological disorders. His 1973 book [[Awakenings (book)|Awakenings]] was\nadapted into an Academy Award-nominated film of the same name in 1990 starring\nRobin Williams and Robert De Niro. He and his book [[Musicophilia|Musicophilia:\nTales of Music and the Brain]] were the subject of \"Musical Minds\", an episode\nof the PBS series [[Nova (TV series)|Nova]].\n","linknr":555,"url":"Oliver_Sacks","recorded":1374520843,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Oliver_Sacks&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Oliver_Sacks&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/